===Vehicles===

====Land Ambulance====
The German EMS system's vehicles come in a wide variety of shapes and sizes. All of its vehicles must conform to most aspects of the requirements of European standard [[CEN 1789]] as reflected in the German standard [[DIN]] EN 1789 (types A-C) or German standard DIN 75079.  The visual identity requirements of the European standard are not yet being followed.
The three major types of vehicle are:
# The [[:de:Krankentransportwagen|Krankentransportwagen]] (KTW), a van-type ambulance used for non-emergency transport. It conforms to DIN EN 1789-A1/A2: "Patient Transport Ambulance single/multiple patient"
# The [[:de:Rettungswagen|Rettungswagen]] (RTW), a larger van used for emergencies. It conforms to DIN EN 1789-C "Mobile Intensive Care Unit"
# The [[:de:Notarzteinsatzfahrzeug|Notarzteinsatzfahrzeug]] (NEF), a station wagon or small van. Its purpose is to bring the ''Notarzt'' (EMS Physician Field Responder) to the scene of the emergency, when required. It conforms to DIN 75079

Additionally, the [[:de:Mehrzweckfahrzeug|Mehrzweckfahrzeug]] (MZF), or multi-purpose vehicle &ndash; often referred to as a ''Notfallkrankenwagen'' or ''Kombinationsfahrzeug (KOM)'' &ndash; serves a dual role as patient transport vehicle and as backup for emergency responses and usually conforms to type B of DIN EN 1789.

Other vehicles that are also employed include [[helicopter]]s for the performance of [[air ambulance]] services and, in some coastal areas, boats.
